<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Divided opposition hands victory to Moi: Whole tribes come
out against ruling party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EARLY returns from Kenya's elections showed yesterday the country had voted
on divisive tribal lines with President Daniel arap Moi heading for victory
on a minority of the vote because of a split among opposition supporters
among three main challengers.
For the first time in Kenya's history, however, yesterday's provisional
results revealed the extent of the unpopularity of the ruling party Kanu and
the solid opposition of several provinces and tribes to the continued rule
of Mr Moi.
The results also showed that the opposition would have swept to power if it
had agreed an electoral pact and united behind one presidential candidate
instead of fragmenting into different parties based on tribalism and
personal greed for power.
Political observers said last night that Mr Moi faced a considerable
challenge in trying to rule a divided Kenya.
With results in the presidential race announced in 51 of 188 constituencies
by last night Mr Moi had won 600,377 (48 per cent) out of 1.2m votes
counted.
Mr Moi's lead was artificially inflated by the early declaration of many
results from his power base of Rift Valley province. Mr Kenneth Matiba, the
presidential candidate of Ford-Asili, was leading the race for second place
with 359,345 votes (29 per cent), well ahead of seven other contenders.
In the eight constituencies of the Rift Valley, a Kanu heartland and home to
Mr Moi's Kalenjin people and other pastoralist minority tribes, which had
declared results by last night Mr Moi had won more than 93 per cent of the
presidential vote.
He was also drawing strong support from Coast province and from Northeastern
province, which has been closed off to opposition activity by the
government.
In Western province Mr Moi was in second place behind Mr Matiba with four
results declared.
In the Coast, however, the first results from the provincial capital of
Mombasa town in Changamwe constituency showed a large vote for Jaramogi
Oginga Odinga, Presidential candidate of Ford-Kenya, reflecting the
influence of the banned Islamic Party of Kenya which did an electoral pact
with Ford-Kenya. The IPK was expected to continue to have a favourable
impact on votes for Ford-Kenya in Kwale and Mombasa districts of Coast
province as more results are announced.
Ford Kenya was last night sweeping three of the four districts of Nyanza
province, the homeland of Mr Odinga's Luo tribe. Other opposition parties,
led by Mr Matiba, were also hammering Mr Moi and Kanu in Central and Nairobi
provinces, homeland of the powerful and disenchanted Kikuyu tribe.
In the five of 30 constituencies which had declared presidential results by
last night Mr Moi had won a mere 3 per cent. Mr Matiba led the presidential
race in Nairobi and Central provinces led with nearly 75 per cent of the
vote.
'Moi is going to face a crisis of governability after the elections because
it is impossible to rule Kenya without the Kikuyu and the Kikuyu have now
declared forcefully they are completely in opposition to Moi,' said Mr David
Throup, a Kenya specialist at Keele University who observed the elections.
See Editorial Comment, Page 10
</TEXT>
