<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Customs keeps up defences as EC's trade barriers fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAVELLERS may not notice customs checks after the single European market
begins life at midnight tonight, but officials will still be keeping a close
watch on them.
Hundreds of uniformed officers and administrative staff at borders
throughout the European Community will be replaced by more discreet
surveillance and intelligence-gathering.
'The question is not what you see at the borders after January 1, but what
you don't see,' said one British Customs and Excise official. Its planners
estimate that while some 400 of the 3,500 UK border staff will be affected
by the abolition of EC customs controls, only about 12 will lose their jobs.
The authorities are confident that by reallocating staff, they will be able
to curtail the efforts of smugglers and terrorists at least as well as now.
They stress that all important drug seizures in recent years were based on
intelligence operations, not random border searches.
Some staff no longer required in person at the borders will still be needed
in a more discreet role monitoring the flows of traffic and people. Similar
changes to customs services are taking place in other EC countries, although
many - particularly the southern European states - have routinely relied
more on intelligence and internal controls than on border checks.
Customs controls between the UK and Ireland have long been working in the
way being adopted elsewhere, because fixed posts are too vulnerable to
terrorist attack.
Customs officials will no longer have the power to stop and search at random
those travelling from other EC countries, but they will be able to
interrogate any who match their 'profiles' of suspicious characters.
Many staff are being reassigned inland as investigators in London and the 22
customs collection divisions around the country, where they will gather
intelligence on the movements of suspected smugglers and value added tax
fraudsters. They are coy about explaining how this will work, but it will
include gathering tip-offs and assembling profiles of likely suspects to be
pursued. Publicans in Dover have been approached for help in alerting
officials to anyone they consider suspicious.
Other employees will become excise verification officers. They have powers
to search suspect vehicles anywhere in the UK and can inspect shops to check
if supplies are coming from registered traders. Further staff are being
moved to other customs duties, such as dealing with the new statistical and
VAT procedures introduced from tomorrow.
Many uniformed customs officers will still be needed at UK borders. They
will cope with EC and non-EC citizens arriving from outside the Community,
who will still pass through a green channel and stop at a 'red spot' if they
have goods to declare. Travellers, of whatever nationality, arriving from
elsewhere in the EC will pass through a new blue channel.
Most of the job changes required will be complete by the end of 1993.
Mixed feelings over the single market, Page 4
</TEXT>
