<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Mixed feelings over the single market: Andrew Jack looks at
why some companies are grumbling about EC changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMS and Excise officials have been gathering in an ageing tower block at
Southend in the past few months to prepare the statistical systems needed
for the single European market.
Meanwhile, in a newly built office in Newry, Northern Ireland, staff
re-allocated from the border with the republic are starting work on the
administration of the value added tax procedures which will be required from
tomorrow.
In the 22 VAT collection regions around the country investigations officers
have been added to strengthen controls against smuggling, fraud and tax
evasion.
In spite of all these preparations the single market - and Customs as its
frontline representative - has been the subject of significant grumbling by
a number of companies.
Many appear unaware, even now, of the changes which will be required. Others
have received blank stares or conflicting advice from trade associations and
consultants. Still more have been waiting for details to be announced.
From tomorrow border controls for traders with other EC countries will be
abolished. The old statistical document with 54 questions which had to be
presented at each frontier will be no more.
In its place businesses will have to complete two new boxes on their VAT
returns, giving the value of imports or exports to other EC states. Those
for which either figure exceeds Pounds 35,000 for the year will be required
to file monthly statistical forms and regular sales-listing forms to
Customs.
Those likely to find the transition most painful are the businesses just
above this threshold - too large to escape the extra requirements, too small
to have dedicated staff to deal with them.
Many see the new burdens without appreciating the benefits of increased
speed at border crossings because they used to delegate this administration
to customs agents.
Meanwhile, the lack of detail has stalled final preparations. The commodity
code directories required to complete the new statistical forms and the
final document listing new procedures for businesses were distributed in the
past few weeks.
Customs has taken the blame for the slow progress of its political masters.
It was only in mid-December that EC finance ministers drew up agreements
dealing with the treatment of antiques and yachts, for example.
At that time they initialled a simplification directive on the subject of
'triangulation' by which a company in one EC country supplies a customer in
a second state through a sub-contractor in a third. Some accountants argue
that its interpretation remains unclear.
Privately, Customs officials express despair at the attitude of many
businesses - accusing them of being far more eager to criticise the changes
than to embrace the opportunities of the single market.
They also say that there has been some self-interested scaremongering by
consultants and computer suppliers hoping to generate extra business. They
argue that businesses have managed to cope with substantial changes to the
tax system before now.
They stress that the UK has fought with other member states to reduce the
burdens on business. The number of questions on the new statistical form has
been kept to a minimum, and the proportion of companies required to file
them has been cut to far lower levels than in other EC states.
Customs has completed personal visits to almost all the 30,000 traders
affected by the new procedures, in addition to an extensive programme over
many months of distributing publicity material and hosting presentations.
That compares favourably with the position elsewhere. Mr Peter Wilmott, head
of the EC Commission's indirect tax and customs directorate, admits that
there has been a significant 'information gap' in some member states. 'It
has been difficult to get firms to listen, but many member states have not
made enough effort,' he says.
In the past few weeks countries such as Spain, Italy, Portugal and Greece
have redoubled their efforts to notify businesses of the changes required.
'Nobody believes we will have all the rules and that firms will know what
they are meant to be doing on January 1,' he says. 'Until you test it, you
can't be sure.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-72</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CL4A8ABHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921231
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Sharp drop in executives' pay rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALMOST 15 per cent of private-sector employers froze the pay of their
executives while average pay awards for executives fell sharply in the third
quarter of this year, according to IDS, the independent pay research group.
Pay awards for executives averaged 4 per cent in the three months to October
compared with 4.9 per cent in the previous quarter, the group says in its
survey of more than 105 organisations. Pay awards for all staff in the
private sector averaged 4 per cent in October and November.
In its survey IDS says: 'Economic uncertainty and the recession have had a
dramatic impact, leading to a sharp fall in the general level of salary
increases.' The survey adds to the evidence that a recent spate of very
large pay rises for executives runs counter to the norm.
The survey, by the IDS Top Pay Unit, shows that executives continue to win
pay rises above the rate of inflation.
The Treasury forecast in the Autumn Statement that underlying inflation,
measured by the retail prices index excluding mortgage-interest payments,
would be at 3.75 per cent by the end of this year and would rise at the same
average rate next year.
At a large employer which awarded the highest rise among the companies in
the survey, junior and middle managers received a salary increase of 4.5 per
cent, as well as individual merit increases averaging 2.5 per cent.
Leadership is only the fifth most important characteristic of a good top
manager, a survey suggested yesterday.
Most important was ability to manage change, said the report on more than
1,000 private-sector and public-sector bodies questioned by management
consultancy Kinsley Lord. Next was enabling staff to make best use of their
skills and improve performance.
IDS Top Pay Unit Review 142. IDS, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
