<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Yugoslav army 'will stand up to west'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By A Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MILITARY intervention by western forces in the former Yugoslavia would meet
fierce resistance from the Yugoslav army, Gen Zivota Panic, the Yugoslav
army's chief of staff, said in Belgrade yesterday.
'If intervention comes, we will defend our freedom, independence and
territory with all means at our disposal,' he declared. 'Our forecasts show
that the danger of military intervention has objectively increased in recent
days. 'We must inform the world that this is a new genocide and we will not
allow it.'
Gen Panic's warning came as Britain moved a step closer towards backing
military intervention against Serbia. Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary,
said in a newspaper article published yesterday that he could now 'imagine
armed action against them to prevent a general Balkan war'.
The Foreign Office emphasised Britain was losing patience with the Serbs,
although the government still saw direct military involvement as far from
inevitable. It stressed Mr Hurd had also said in the Daily Telegraph article
that, 'democratic opinion would not support us in military occupation over
years, with the inevitable costs and casualties.'
General Panic, who commanded the Serbian operation last year that left the
Croatian city of Vukovar a pile of rubble, asserted the West had conspired
to break up Yugoslavia, but his forces could grow from a peacetime level of
120,000 to 600,000 in wartime. It was possible to mobilise up to 2m
reservists, he said.
The UN mediator Lord David Owen was in Belgrade yesterday in preparation for
talks on the Yugoslav crisis this weekend in Geneva.
Mr Milan Panic, the Yugoslav prime minister, yesterday also condemned the
threat of military intervention. 'The politicians will sit out military
intervention secure in their bunkers,' he said. Speaking in Belgrade, he
rejected as unconstitutional a parliamentary vote on Tuesday night naming a
vice-premier to lead the Government until a newly-elected parliament is
installed early next year.
'I will not run away,' Mr Panic said, dismissing as 'lunacy' calls by
ultra-nationalists for his arrest. 'This is how fascism started in Nazi
Germany. We have to stop this in our country.' Mr Panic, a Serbian-American
millionaire returned to Yugoslavia in July to take up the premiership.
Mr Panic lost presidential elections to the Serb leader Mr Slobodon
Milosevic on December 20, but he has charged that the polls were unfair.
Editorial comment, Page 10
</TEXT>
