<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Supermarkets begin fierce price-cut battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J SAINSBURY, the UK's biggest supermarket chain, prompted an aggressive
round of price-cutting by grocery retailers yesterday as it pledged to
reduce prices on 750 lines from Sunday, including savings of 50 per cent on
some items.
Competitors Tesco and Safeway quickly unveiled details of their own January
promotions, raising the prospect of a full-scale price war, but most
industry analysts dismissed this possibility.
'It's not the start of a price war, but it is a significant step up in the
level of promotional skirmishing,' said Mr Nick Bubb, retailing analyst at
Morgan Stanley.
In the stock market, food retailers' shares were heavily marked down.
Analysts said the price-cutting had been seen as an excuse for shareholders
to take profits in the sector.
They added that Sainsbury's move was a carefully planned campaign to bolster
its market position. The supermarket group said its sales over Christmas
were ahead of budget. Its campaign was likely to put most pressure on Tesco,
on smaller chains such as Gateway and Co-op, and on some independent
retailers.
Tesco and Safeway said their promotions had been planned some time ago, and
dismissed Sainsbury's announcement as a marketing gimmick, a repeat of last
year's January promotion which they claimed had promised much but delivered
little.
'It's very surprising that Sainsbury should repeat the same exercise as last
year, when the reality was far different from customers' perceptions, and it
had no impact on our business,' Tesco said.
Mr Robin Whitbread, marketing director at Sainsbury, countered that the
promotion involved reductions on 750 items, compared with 500 last year. It
would also include substantial reductions of 25 per cent or more on about
100 items, compared with fewer than 30 last year, and would cover a wider
range of goods.
The campaign, moreover, was not limited to January but would continue for an
unspecified period, with discounted items being rotated regularly.
Tesco said it would launch its January promotion on Monday, involving more
than 1,000 lines. This would include at least a third off more than 100
items, with many at half price.
Safeway said it already had 1,000 special offers and would launch a new year
promotion on Monday including 50 per cent savings on some basic items.
VG complaint to MMC, Page 4
Lex, Page 12
London stocks, Page 28
</TEXT>
