<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 92 / Women to the fore in new honours list
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN have a higher-than-usual profile in the New Year Honours list
published today.
Six dames are created and two of the weightier political honours go to Mrs
Shirley Williams, the former Labour cabinet minister and a founder-member of
the Social Democratic party, and Baroness Blatch, the education minister.
Mrs Williams is the only life peer created this time.
In other respects, the list - the last before Mr John Major's review of the
honours system takes effect - is traditional in its mix of politicians and
people from business, the arts and sport. However, the prime minister is
said to have put particular emphasis on charity work as well as other
achievements.
Mr Duncan Nichol, chief executive of the National Health Service management
executive, and Mr Robert Balchin, chairman of the grant-maintained schools
foundation, become knights in recognition of their contribution to the
government's reforms in health and education.
Among the business figures honoured are five knights: Mr John Keswick,
chairman of Hambros bank; Mr Robert Clarke, chairman of United Biscuits; Mr
Christopher Lewinton, chairman and chief executive of TI group, the
aerospace, seals and tubes group; Mr Geoffrey Mulcahy, chairman and chief
executive of Kingfisher, the retail group; and Mr Paul Nicholson, chairman
of Vaux group, the Sunderland-based brewer and hotels operator.
In the diplomatic honours list, Mr William Purves, chairman of HSBC
Holdings, parent of Hongkong Bank and Midland, becomes a knight for public
and commercial services in Hong Kong.
Baroness Blatch is the only member of the government to become a privy
counsellor, although three senior Tory backbenchers are similarly honoured.
They include Sir Peter Hordern, seen by many at Westminster as the most able
Tory MP never to have been a minister, and Sir John Wheeler, formerly
chairman of the cross-party home affairs committee.
Mr Cranley Onslow, who lost the chairmanship of the 1922 committee of Tory
backbenchers, is knighted, as is Mr Terence Higgins, formerly chairman of
the cross-party Treasury committee. Mr Roger Moate and Mr Jerry Wiggin,
long-serving but not invariably loyal Tory backbenchers, also become
knights.
Mr David Frost, the broadcaster, becomes a knight and, in the arts world, so
do Mr Malcolm Arnold, the composer, and Mr Anthony Hopkins, the actor.
Novelist Catherine Cookson becomes a dame and the writer Sir Victor
Pritchett becomes a companion of honour.
Mr Jimmy Young, Mrs Thatcher's favourite interviewer, whose radio programme
celebrates 20 years next year, becomes a CBE, as does Mr Frank Barlow,
managing director of Pearson, which owns the Financial Times.
Honours list, Page 18
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
