<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / UK seeks opt-out from employment rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK is to seek an opt-out from the requirements of a European directive
which has caused uncertainty about public services contracted out to the
private sector.
The directive can prevent companies cutting pay and conditions of staff they
take on after mergers and acquisitions. When an 'undertaking' is
'transferred', staff who transfer may retain their existing pay and
conditions, except for pensions.
Companies and government officials are unsure whether the directive applies
to compulsory competitive tendering and so-called 'market-testing' in local
and central government. Contractors and employers' organisations have called
for clarification. Conflicting legal opinions have been given in the absence
of a firm ruling.
The government, which is extending contracting out to Whitehall services,
has dismissed the debate over the regulations as a 'red herring' which will
have, at worst, a limited effect.
Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment minister, will seek an opt-out from the
directive under the year-long subsidiarity review of the proper
responsibilities of national and European authorities agreed at the
Edinburgh summit. The government has consistently rejected an extension of
EC influence over employment matters.
The employment department said: 'Mr Forsyth will seek to have the directive
withdrawn on the grounds of subsidiarity.'
But it is not clear that an opt-out would be possible; an annex to the
Edinburgh agreement gives conflicting signals on the Commission's view on
the application of subsidiarity to social policy. Some legislation is
excluded from the review.
The Trades Union Congress said the government was unlikely to win another
opt-out. A TUC official said: 'The government can scarcely take comfort in
the Edinburgh summit which agreed to supplement European social legislation
with additional measures and to implement all the provisions of the social
chapter. It also limited UK demands that 71 European measures be withdrawn
to 21.'
Expensive undertaking, Page 4
</TEXT>
