<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / Collor quits but senate votes to continue impeachment
process
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASILIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRAZILIAN senate pressed ahead last night with the impeachment of Mr
Fernando Collor de Mello over corruption charges, despite the president's
resignation in an attempt to halt the decisive session of his trial.
The vote to continue the impeachment process, by 73 to 8, brought to a
climax the battle over the political career of Mr Collor, who had been
suspended from office since September when Congress approved the impeachment
charges.
Final impeachment of Mr Collor, which would require a two-thirds majority of
senators and which looked likely last night, would lead to his being banned
from public office for eight years.
By resigning, Mr Collor loses his presidential immunity. He could face
criminal charges.
A spokesman for Mr Collor said 'the president had resigned because the whole
country knew that the sentence was already delivered'. The senate decision
to proceed with impeachment came despite a request from Mr Collor's lawyer
for the hearing to be halted, given that the president had resigned.
Mr Itamar Franco, who had been acting president and who was sworn in
yesterday as Mr Collor's successor, is expected to address the nation this
morning. Last night, at the presidential palace, he described the new
economic order in Brazil as 'unjust' and said it had to be changed.
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, the foreign minister, said: 'This will now
allow us to get on with governing the country.'
After a volatile session the Sao Paulo stock market closed down 1.2 per
cent.
The parliamentary drama began when the Supreme Court chief justice called on
Mr Collor's attorney, Mr Jose Moura Rocha, to begin questioning his first
witness. The lawyer said he had spoken to Mr Collor and that the president
would resign.
He then passed a note in Mr Collor's hand to senate president Mauro
Benevides which said: 'I am resigning my mandate as president of the
republic, a position to which I was elected in the elections of November 15
and December 17 1989.'
Mr Franco, 62, read the oath of office before a roaring gallery of
supporters singing the national anthem and chanting: 'The people united will
never be defeated.' People in the galleries tossed T-shirts emblazoned with
'Collorbuster' to the Chamber of Deputies and teenage activists cheered the
inauguration.
Brazil's beached playboy bows out, Page 2
