<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE version of Tosca to be shown between 6.30 and 8.25 on BBC2 is the one
originally relayed live from Rome in July. With Domingo as Cavaradossi,
Catherine Malfitano as Tosca, and Ruggero Raimondi as Scarpia it was
performed on the Rome locations and at the times specified in the script. It
can now be seen in one evening without breaks.
If Tchaikovsky appeals more than Puccini, Radio 3 is offering Symphonies 1
and 4 in its concert series The Tchaikovsky Symphonies (7.30). The St
Petersburg Philharmonic performs under Yuri Temirkanov.
The situation comedy about night security men, Nightingales, which begins a
new batch on C4 at 10.30, is at its best when the most absurd of fantasies
are mixed with reality. The acting is extraordinarily strong with James
Ellis (once of 'Z Cars'), Robert Lindsay (so good in 'GBH') and David
Threlfall (unforgettable in 'Nicholas Nickleby') playing the security
guards.
Radio 4's series about radio itself, The Friend In The Corner (11.00),
considers 1967 when the Home, Light and Third disappeared and local radio
first took to the air.
