<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / Contracting out may prove an expensive undertaking: The row
over European rules for transferring staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES bidding for contracts to provide services in the public sector
often rely on cutting wages and staff benefits to make a profit. But some of
the attractions for companies in bidding for contracts are now in doubt.
Recent rulings by the European Court of Justice have led unions and some
legal experts to argue that successful bidders may be bound to honour the
pay and benefits of employees they retain.
If they are right the case for contracting out could be seriously
undermined, as labour represents about 80 per cent of the cost of public
services.
Many of those who are preparing the current round of compulsory competitive
tendering and market-testing in local and central government are deeply
concerned.
At the heart of the dispute are the UK's 1981 Transfer of Undertakings
(Protection of Employment) regulations which were designed to implement the
European Commission's 1977 Acquired Rights directive.
Where there is a 'transfer' of an 'undertaking' the regulations oblige
employers to observe the contractual rights and obligations - except
pensions - of employees they retain. If these regulations do apply, then in
theory workers continue with no break in their employment rights.
The central question is whether the regulations normally apply to
contracting out. The government says the regulations can apply in the public
sector, but ministers have insisted they do not apply where local
authorities contract out in-house services under tendering legislation or in
the contracting out of Whitehall services.
Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment minister, is sufficiently irritated by
the confusion to seek a UK opt-out from the EC directive. He argues that it
should be left to national governments.
Mr John McMullen, head of the employment unit and a partner at solicitors
Simpson Curtis, said: 'For each contract, companies and government officials
need to ask themselves whether there is likely to be a 'relevant transfer'
of an 'undertaking'. Only if both conditions are satisfied will the
regulations apply.'
All cases must be considered individually but there are some generally
agreed tests. First, an 'undertaking' is usually defined as an economic
entity with, for example, its own balance sheet. Then, the more similar the
function of the entity after the transfer, the more likely it is the courts
would rule its 'identity' was intact.
Finally, the easier it is to point to physical evidence of a transfer, for
example equipment and staff, the more likely it is the regulations apply.
Legal opinion is still divided over when the regulations will apply. A
recent ruling by the European Court of Justice appears to reinforce the
arguments of those who claim the regulations will normally apply to
contracting out.
This month the court indicated that the transfer of a management contract
could constitute a transfer under the regulations, and that the sole
question for national courts was whether the undertaking had retained its
identity after the transfer had taken place.
Each case would have to be considered on its facts in national courts.
Firm court rulings on contracting out in the UK should reduce the
uncertainty and several cases are pending.
Meanwhile the unions hope they have found fresh support from the EC in their
efforts to curb the market-led policies of the UK government.
Some companies say that, whatever the outcome of the cases, they will not be
dissuaded from bidding for contracts. Some contractors for skilled services,
such as information technology, even say they prefer to transfer staff under
the regulations.
They rely on retaining experienced staff who are often earning less than
their counterparts in the private sector. Mr Lynton Barker, the partner at
accountancy firm Coopers &amp; Lybrand responsible for advising companies
preparing to bid for Whitehall services, said that in cost calculations for
a five-year contract overheads and technology would be at least as important
as labour.
There remains one clear reason the regulations do matter. Failure to apply
them could expose the government and contractors to claims for compensation.
Already unions are preparing retrospective claims on behalf of members who,
they say, suffered losses as a result of earlier rounds of contracting out.
</TEXT>
