FT  30 DEC 92 / Protest at London NHS plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO HOSPITAL closures should take place in London until alternative services
are available as part of a planned programme of change, the Association of
London Authorities says today.
The Labour-controlled association has told Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health
secretary, in its response to the Tomlinson report on London health care
that the study does not provide a sufficient basis for closing hospitals or
reducing medical teaching.
It says London has a range of particular health needs, including high
accident and mortality rates, high levels of mental illness and a lack of
local clinics and small hospitals.
The report recommends reducing the number of hospital beds in the capital
and transferring resources to family doctor and community services. The
association says, difficulties facing general practitioners in the capital -
with almost half in poor premises and 40 per cent working alone - are among
the particular problems that need to be addressed before closing hospitals.
The association also urges a single regional authority to plan services in
the capital.
Ministers are due to decide on the Tomlinson report, which contains
controversial proposals including the closure of St Bartholomew's hospital
in the City, next month.
