<TEXT>
A RENEWED campaign to put jobs at the top of the political agenda will be
launched early in the new year, Labour pledged yesterday.
Mr John Smith, the party leader, said: 'In 1993 Labour will campaign with
vigour and determination for an end to rising unemployment and for a
programme of national recovery based on the vital importance of investment
and training.'
At the heart of the campaign will be a demand for an emergency employment
programme to be introduced before the budget in March. The need for skilled
jobs to help rebuild the economy will also be emphasised.
The party's call for action to create jobs in the construction industry and
to improve and expand training programmes will come against a background of
continuing rises in the jobless numbers. The TUC expects unemployment to
rise by about 50,000 a month over the next three months, reaching 3m in
January or February.
Mr Frank Dobson, the shadow employment secretary, gave a taste of the type
of Westminster campaigning that ministers can expect. He published a list of
the increases in unemployment over the past two years in cabinet ministers'
constituencies. The total in the 20 seats has more than doubled, rising from
34,000 in November 1990 to 71,000 in November 1992.
Labour's initiative also contains a significant element of grassroots
campaigning. Material issued to local party branches this month says the key
task is to link the government's difficulties over pit closures with the
wider issues of recession and unemployment.
