<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / Lebanon rejects joint aid for deportees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Lebanese authorities yesterday rejected an Israeli proposal that both
governments should simultaneously allow the delivery of humanitarian aid to
the 415 expelled Palestinians who have been stranded in south Lebanon for
the last 12 days.
Mr Rafif al-Hariri, the Lebanese prime minister, dismissed a suggestion from
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, his Israeli counterpart, that medical supplies be
forwarded from Israel to the deportees' camp in no-man's land between
Israeli and Lebanese forces, while food and fresh water was delivered from
Lebanese-controlled territory.
He then refused to allow Mr James Jonah, a UN undersecretary general, to
visit the deportees, alleged by Israel to be Islamic fundamentalist
militants. 'Jonah is wasting his time with us. This is a wasted trip. Our
position is firm,' Mr Hariri said.
Mr Jonah was sent to the region by Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN
secretary general, following the adoption of Security Council resolution 799
calling for the return of the deportees to the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Lebanon, backed by Syria and other Arab states, says Israel should
implement the resolution immediately.
Israel confirmed yesterday that it was willing to take back 10 men whom it
said were deported mistakenly. But the army said they would be put on trial
when they returned. Mr Rabin, who will see Mr Jonah for the second time this
week in Jerusalem today, has refused to consider reversing the deportations.
Mr Shimon Peres, the foreign minister, said the deportations were successful
because they had hit at extremists opposed to Middle East peace talks,
without destroying the talks themselves. But he admitted the issue had
caused some negative effects - including the postponment until February of a
visit by a European Community delegation to discuss closer EC-Israeli
economic co-operation.
The Israeli finance ministry is to utilise Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.7m) in US
loan guarantees granted earlier this year to aid the absorption immigrants
from the former Soviet Union. This would start next March, when Israel would
seek to borrow Dollars 1bn backed by the guarantees.
</TEXT>
