<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 92 / AMR agrees share stake deal with Canadian Airlines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMR, the parent company of American Airlines, yesterday announced plans to
invest CDollars 246m (USDollars 192m) into a restructured Canadian Airlines,
in exchange for a 33 per cent economic interest in the loss-making carrier
and a 25 per cent voting stake.
The share stake deal comes as part of a broader agreement between AMR and
PWA, Canadian's parent company, under which Canadian has agreed to sign a
20-year services contract with AMR. This requires the Canadian airline to
buy a range of airline administrative services from American.
The services contract is designed to cut Canadian's costs, but would
probably eliminate around 1,200-1,300 jobs. AMR says the agreement should
produce revenues of Dollars 2bn over the two decades, with the first full
year generating Dollars 115m.
Canadian, which lost CDollars 105.6m after tax in the first nine months of
1992, will also tie up its frequent flier programme with American's, so that
Canadian passengers can earn credits for flights with American (and vice
versa).
Canadian's international routes, mainly to Europe and Asia, will remain
under its direct control.
AMR said that this was 'the most comprehensive package' of services it had
ever sold to another carrier.
Among the administrative functions which the Canadian carrier will buy from
AMR are accounting, data-processing and communications operations.
The deal is a key step in Canadian's restructuring. AMR will receive
convertible preferred stock, providing it with the 25 per cent voting stake
in Canadian. PWA will retain 75 per cent. The US carrier will be entitled to
designate two of the eight members of Canadian's board of directors.
However, AMR said it would not control any of Canadian's 'major strategic
business decisions'.
The deal requires both US and Canadian government approval. A tie-up between
the two carriers has been complicated by the requirement that Canadian
extract itself from the Gemini electronic reservation system, in order to
join American's Sabre system. Its attempted withdrawal has prompted
litigation.
The two airlines estimate that the deal will be finalised by autumn 1993.
</TEXT>
