FT  29 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A hidden camera in Truckers (8.00 C4) reveals how an international lorry
driver talks and bribes his way through border controls and police checks in
Europe.
Winter Dreams (BBC2, also at 8.00) is a ballet by Kenneth MacMillan which he
re-worked for television some time before his death in October. Inspired by
Chekhov's 'Three Sisters' and set to music by Tchaikovsky, it is a study of
the passions and longings of the three sisters who are danced by Darcey
Bussell, Viviana Durante and Nicola Tranah.
Rowan Atkinson's 'silent comedy' skits leave me stone cold so I shall not
watch Merry Christmas Mr Bean (8.30 ITV) but millions will, and the
programme may well win awards like its predecessors.
However I shall be trying the opening episode of The Vampyr since its full
title is The Vampyr - A Soap Opera (9.00 BBC2) and the idea of up-dating a
19th century romantic opera seems interesting. It continues daily until
Sunday. That is followed (9.25) by a one-off black comedy from BBC Scotland,
The Bogie Man, starring splendid Robbie Coltrane as a man of many disguises.
