<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 92 / MMI agrees deal with Zurich Insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZURICH Insurance yesterday announced that it had agreed in priciple to take
over a large part of the business of Municipal Mutual Insurance, the
troubled specialist in policies for local authorities, after months of
talks.
Under the deal, Zurich Insurance will acquire MMI's local authority
liability business, personal insurance policies and a range of commercial
insurance business. Zurich is also likely to employ about 1,800 of MMI's
2,000 staff.
The agreement follows prolonged negotiations between the two companies,
starting in October. Zurich was reluctant to assume liabilities on policies
already underwritten by MMI, which used to insure 90 per cent of local
authorities.
Zurich is not thought to be taking financial responsibility for MMI's past
liabilities but is taking on the administration of past liabilities with
current business, using the staff and assets that will transfer from MMI.
Zurich said that MMI policyholders would be offered renewal terms. It said
it would employ all MMI staff directly involved in the business being
transferred, as well as all relevant systems such as computers and working
assets.
Zurich said that the companies anticipated finalising contracts in January
subject to final board and regulatory approval.
MMI said that employees of both companies had already been briefed on the
agreement, and said it was pleased that the central administrative core of
the company had not had to be broken up.
An agreement had been widely expected after Zurich offered new facilities in
November to 300 local authorities whose policies were coming up for renewal.
It also offered fresh cover to about 31,000 individual MMI policyholders.
The deal will be an important step for Zurich Insurance towards its target
of expanding significantly in Britain. In 1990 its share of the British
non-life insurance market was 1.1 per cent and it ranked 20th by size, but
it was the third biggest life insurer in Europe last year.
MMI withdrew from the insurance market in September, leaving a number of
local authorities without cover. This followed the breakdown of earlier
rescue talks with La Garantie Mutuelle des Fonctionnaires, the French
insurer.
The company first encountered trouble last year when it had losses of more
than Pounds 250m on its liability business. It was affected by claims over
fires in schools, as well as potential claims from former occupants of
children's homes, which led to it breaching the DTI's solvency guidelines.
</TEXT>
