<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 92 / Few food companies see upturn in demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER than half of Britain's larger food, drink and consumer goods
manufacturers and their suppliers said they had noticed an upturn in demand
for their products by the middle of this month, according to a survey.
Almost half of those which had experienced no recovery expected one to start
in the first or second quarter of next year. Twenty-five per cent said they
expected no improvement until 1994.
A small majority of the companies did not want sterling to rejoin the
European exchange rate mechanism in the next 12 months. This view was
particularly strong among British-owned companies.
The telephone survey covered directors of 181 manufacturing companies with
annual sales of more than Pounds 5m, most of them in consumer businesses. It
was carried out for the Financial Times between December 14 and 21 by
Nielsen, the market research company.
About two thirds of the companies surveyed expected UK sales and exports to
increase next year, while about a quarter believed they would stay the same.
Slightly more than a quarter planned to increase adver-tising spending, and
about the same proportion expected their staff numbers in Britain to
increase. However, 16 per cent expected their staff numbers to fall.
Eighty-five per cent said recent currency fluctuations had affected their
business, and just over a third said they had to rethink their production
and distribution arrangements in Europe as a result.
</TEXT>
