<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 92 / Russia and US edge towards N-arms treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Lawrence Eagleburger, US secretary of state, and his Russian counterpart,
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, edged closer to a historic nuclear arms reduction treaty
yesterday, although doubts remained after several hours of talks, Reuter
reports from Geneva.
'We're making progress,' Mr Eagleburger said at a dinner he hosted for Mr
Kozyrev at the end of a day of talks. But asked if he could complete the
Start II treaty today, he said: 'I can't tell you. We're not going to say
anything more until we've got this thing finished. We will be doing our
best.'
Earlier, Mr Kozyrev had voiced optimism that he and Mr Eagleburger could
succeed in efforts to complete the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty before
President George Bush left office on January 20.
'I am ready to bet a bottle of whisky and say that we will do such work here
which will make it possible for our presidents to have a positive decision
after our negotiations today,' he said.
At the dinner the Russian foreign minister said he still expected to win his
bet. 'So far my glass is full,' he said.
But Mr Richard Boucher, a US spokesman, had said after the initial meeting
that it was clear the talks would have to continue today. Mr Eagle-burger
plans to return to Washington this afternoon, regardless of whether or not
he has secured a deal.
Start II aims to reduce the two countries' stocks of nuclear weapons by
about two-thirds and eliminate land-based missiles with multiple warheads,
the most dangerous category of cold war weapons.
As the talks began there were three issues separating the sides: the fate of
Russian SS18 silos, the role of Russian SS19 missiles and the question of
which US bombers should be counted under treaty limits.
The US relaxed its earlier position that all silos housing the 154 SS18
missiles should be destroyed. Under the treaty the missiles would be
eliminated but Russia had asked to preserve the silos to protect mobile SS25
missiles.
On SS19s, Mr Eagleburger said Washington was prepared to allow the Russians
to 'download' five warheads from some of their 170 missiles and thus
preserve them under the treaty.
On the issue of bombers, the US wants to retain the option of loading
nuclear weapons on its B1 aircraft as it retires B52 bombers. But Russia
says the B1s should be counted under the treaty limits if Washington wants
to preserve that right.
</TEXT>
