FT  29 DEC 92 / Brenda Dean seeks top Acas post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MS BRENDA DEAN, formerly Britain's senior woman trade unionist, and Mr Mike
Bett, deputy chairman of British Telecommunications, are the front-runners
to take over the chairmanship of Acas, the government conciliation service,
David Goodhart writes.
Sir Douglas Smith, the current chairman, retires next year and his successor
will be announced next month.
Along with several other prominent public-sector jobs, such as chairmanships
of the Commission for Racial Equality and the Equal Opportunities
Commission, the Acas job has for the first time been publicly advertised
rather than filled privately.
Another prominent applicant is thought to be Mr John Hougham, head of
industrial relations at Ford UK. Mr Hougham would neither confirm nor deny
that he had applied.
Acas's terms of reference will be changed under the Employment Bill,
currently going through committee stage in the Commons. Its new remit will
be to 'improve' industrial relations rather than 'encourage the extension of
collective bargaining'.
Ms Dean, 50, former leader of the Sogat print union, resigned in May as
deputy general secretary of the GPMU, which was formed by the merger of
Sogat and the NGA.
